post_text:
To comply with the New York State mandate that we do a daily screener for those in the building, South Seneca has partnered with Cayuga Health to make use of their screener tool.

Families of students will receive an email from the system directing them to a brief registration process. After that, you will receive an email each day with a unique link to use to complete the screener.

Depending on your answers to the 6 daily health screening questions, you get a ‚Äúgreen‚Äù or ‚Äúred‚Äù status. Green means your child is clear to come in. For more information click this link: https://www.southseneca.org/article/300698?org=south-seneca

Our online health screening process will launch soon. Anyone seeking entry to a school building or school bus will need to complete and pass our online screening process prior to entry. Please ensure that the school has an email address on file for each family so we can contact you.

Families will need a way to take students‚Äô temperatures at home, we can provide thermometers to families who need them. Please contact the school for help.

Budget Vote Results:

Expenditure budget PASSED 884-350 (71.6%)
Library Proposition PASSED 873-359
Bus Reserve Proposition PASSED 869-367

Board Candidates Brenda Eastman (700 votes), Mike Paparone (618), and Melissa Laverack (605) were elected.

Candidates not elected:
Ralph Malvik (597)
Kristina Dresser (543)
Eleanor Liebsen (206)

THANK YOU to the community, and to all who sent in votes!!

post_text:
The South Seneca Board of Education, at its March 25 board meeting, has accepted an adjustment to the 2019-20 academic calendar, moving three spring break days (from April 7-9) to allow for online and home-based learning to continue those days. The three off days have been moved to March 27, April 3, and April 13. This will allow for a break from academics to occur on three consecutive long weekends: March 27-29, April 3-6, and April 10-13 during our current closure period.

This means that April 7, 8, and 9 will be considered school days from home, with continued communication on those days from teachers on academics.

It is important to note that our food deliveries will continue to take place during our closure period on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays as previously established, including the academic ‚Äòdays off‚Äô on this new calendar.

shared_text:
South Seneca High School News
March 24 at 3:06 PM ¬∑

Congratulations to the following students for having their artwork selected to be sent to the National Scholastic Art Awards which was judged in NYC in January: Ellen Appleby, Damyan Arnold, Hailey Bentley, Mackenzie Coyle, Jenika Halsey, Faith Kashella, McKenzie Knapp, and Clay Pollack. These students' works were judged alongside 5000+ artworks in the Northeast Regional-at-Large. The following students won the following awards:

Mackenzie Coyle - Silver Key for "Disillusion"
Mackenzie Coyle - Honorable Mention for "Pink Flowers"
Mackenzie Coyle - Honorable Mention for "Home of the Sparrow"
Jenika Halsey - Honorable Mention for "Family Ties"
McKenzie Knapp - Honorable Mention for "Untamed"

The winners will receive certificates and a silver key pin, as well as have their artwork displayed forever on the Wall of Fame in the HS Art Room. Congratulations to all those that participated and those who received awards for their hardwork and talent!

shared_text:
South Seneca High School News
November 21, 2019 at 7:32 AM ¬∑

On Tuesday, Mr. Matt Barkee observed Hannah Goldberg in her Work Study setting with Finger Lakes 1.

He was beyond impressed. Hannah completed a series of Podcasts. She came up with the concept, all the content, and did all the scheduling to get the people in for them.

Hannah's podcasts are called "The High School Experience." She featured every school in the county. She wrapped them up yesterday and they are being released on the Fingerlakes1 TV site next week.

Mr. Barkee watched Hannah interview some athletes from Mynderse and an all-state band member from Waterloo who is participating in the Macy's parade next week with her school.

Our work study program is another example of how our little school thinks big. Thanks to Mr. Barkee and to Hannah for her great work!

(1:45 p.m.) UPDATE:
School and law enforcement officials have secured the area several times and our lockout is no longer in effect. However, for precautionary reasons, we will continue to keep students inside the building the remainder of the school day. This includes Extended Day.

We will follow our normal dismissal plans for pick ups, bus students, SSAFE and Extended Day.

(original post) South Seneca Elementary School is currently on lockout. A bear cub was reported on school property. We have swept the area and do not see the bear anymore. However, we will keep students inside for the remainder of the day. All staff and visitors must use the main entrance only.

We contacted law enforcement immediately and all students and staff are safe. Otherwise, our school is running business as usual inside the building.

shared_text:
NYS Farm to School Program - CCE Seneca
September 30, 2019 at 9:18 AM ¬∑

After starting seeds, transplanting into the garden, and a long wait over summer, middle school students at South Seneca Central School District got to enjoy their watermelon harvested from the school garden. Next they will be helping harvest the butternut squash that will be featured on their menu in November for their NY Thursday Harvest of the Month. Learning about what it takes to grow our own food and the nutritional benefits of fresh produce is what our Seed to Harvest project is all about. Fresh is best! Eat local, support local, and thank a farmer! Seneca County Cornell Cooperative Extension
#farmtoschool
#seedtoharvest
